{"status":"success","result":"Oh that's a much cleaner design! So Jarvis stays as the single point of contact, but under the hood he can upgrade *himself* — like shifting gears rather than handing off the wheel.\n\nThat sidesteps a lot of the coordination complexity I was looking at. No request files, no polling, no user confirmation dance.\n\nThe interesting design question then becomes: *what triggers the gear shift?*\n\nA few approaches worth thinking about:\n\n• *Task classification* — detect intent upfront (casual chat → small model, code/reasoning/research → bigger model). Fast and cheap but can misclassify\n• *Retry on failure* — Jarvis tries with a lightweight model first, and if the output is below a quality threshold or hits a capability wall, he re-runs with a stronger model. Adds latency but very natural\n• *Explicit capability flags* — certain tools (web search, file ops, code execution) automatically trigger a stronger model since they imply complexity\n• *User-signaled* — power users can say \"think harder on this\" to force the upgrade\n\nThe *retry approach* is probably the most elegant because it keeps the default path fast and cheap, and the escalation is invisible to the user — they just get a better answer with a slight delay.\n\nHow is it structured now — does Jarvis pick the model upfront based on the message, or is there already some dynamic switching happening?","newSessionId":"9ab085a0-060d-41ae-b3d8-a97f4d571171"}
